DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "contextLimitedPolynomial.pl",
#  "PGpolynomialmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("Numeric");
$a2=random(2,5,0.1);
$a1=random($a2+1,9,0.1);
$b2=Real(non_zero_random(-5,5,0.1));
$b1=Real(non_zero_random($b2+1,9,0.1));
$c2=random(1,5,0.1);
$c1=$c2;
$poly1 = Compute("$a1*x**2+$b1*x+$c1")->reduce;
$poly2 = Compute("$a2*x**2+$b2*x+$c2")->reduce;

$a3 = $a1-$a2;
$b3 = $b1-$b2;
$c3 = $c1-$c2;

Context("LimitedPolynomial-Strict");
$ans = Formula("$a3*x**2+$b3*x+$c3")->reduce;


##############################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

An auto company's sales volume (in dollars) can be modeled by [`[$poly1]`], and its costs (in dollars) can be modeled by [`[$poly2]`], where [`x`] represents the number of cars produced. We can calculate the company's net profit by subtracting costs from sales. Find the polynomial which models the company's profit in thousands of dollars.

The company's profit can be modeled by [________________]{$ans} dollars.

END_PGML

###############################################

$s1 = ($b2>0) ? "$b2 x" : "($b2 x)";
$s2 = ($c2>0) ? "$c2" : "($c2)";

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We will subtract the cost polynomial from the sales polynomial:

     [``
         \begin{aligned}
               &\phantom{{}=}\left([$poly1]\right)-\left([$poly2]\right) \\
               & = \left([$a1]x^2-[$a2]x^2\right)+\left([$b1]x-[$s1] \right)+\left([$c1]-[$s2] \right)\\
              & = [$ans]
         \end{aligned}
     ``]

The company's profit can be modeled by [`[$ans]`] dollars.

END_PGML_SOLUTION
